575
00:45:16,240 --> 00:45:18,410
Thanks.

576
00:45:22,380 --> 00:45:25,420
Oh, gosh. It's him.

577
00:45:25,420 --> 00:45:28,490
Hey, Hal!

578
00:45:28,490 --> 00:45:31,190
Welcome home, kiddo.

579
00:45:35,130 --> 00:45:38,800
- Get into these arms,
you little punk.
- Dad.

580
00:45:38,800 --> 00:45:41,330
Finally.

581
00:45:46,470 --> 00:45:50,140
Oh, I hope you had a lousy time at that
camp because

582
00:45:50,140 --> 00:45:52,740
you are not going back.
I missed you too much.

583
00:45:52,750 --> 00:45:53,810
What happened to you, Hal?

584
00:45:55,920 --> 00:45:58,450
Something's changed.

585
00:45:58,450 --> 00:46:00,850
Are you getting taller?

586
00:46:00,850 --> 00:46:02,350
So, what's up, Dad?

587
00:46:04,820 --> 00:46:06,960
I mean, how's Chessy
and everybody?

588
00:46:06,960 --> 00:46:10,530
Great. Everybody's great.
Can't wait to see you.

589
00:46:10,530 --> 00:46:14,330
Eight weeks really is
too long, Hal. A lot's been
happening around here.

590
00:46:14,330 --> 00:46:16,940
A lot's happened to me
too, Dad.

591
00:46:16,940 --> 00:46:21,870
I mean, I feel like
I'm practically a new woman.

592
00:46:21,870 --> 00:46:24,310
What's the matter?
I cut myself shaving?

593
00:46:24,310 --> 00:46:28,550
No, it's just...
just seeing you
for the first time.

594
00:46:28,550 --> 00:46:32,220
I mean, you know...
in so long.

595
00:46:32,220 --> 00:46:34,950
You look taller to me too,
Dad.

596
00:46:34,950 --> 00:46:37,090
Come on, squirt.
Let's get home.

597
00:46:52,200 --> 00:46:54,570
<i>(Dad)</i>Oh, by the way,
thanks for all those
newsy letters.

598
00:46:54,570 --> 00:46:56,880
I'm really glad I bought you
all that personalized
stationery

599
00:46:56,880 --> 00:46:59,280
you just had to have.

600
00:46:59,280 --> 00:47:02,410
- We meant to write,
Dad, but we just...
- "We?"

601
00:47:02,420 --> 00:47:06,480
Oh, me and my friend.
I met this girl at camp
and we got really close.

602
00:47:06,490 --> 00:47:07,550
Great.

603
00:47:07,550 --> 00:47:10,420
Practically like sisters.

604
00:47:10,420 --> 00:47:13,490
- She was a lovely girl.
- "Lovely girl?"

605
00:47:13,490 --> 00:47:17,160
What, all of a sudden you're
so proper?

606
00:47:17,160 --> 00:47:20,530
- Still biting those nails,
I see.
- Dad, you noticed!

607
00:47:20,530 --> 00:47:24,200
What do you mean, "noticed?"
You've been biting
them since you could chew.

608
00:47:24,200 --> 00:47:27,270
But I've decided to stop, Dad.
It's a horrid habit.

609
00:47:27,270 --> 00:47:29,570
"Lovely girl," "horrid habit."

610
00:47:29,580 --> 00:47:32,980
What did I do, send you
to summer camp or
finishing school?

611
00:47:32,980 --> 00:47:35,450
And why do you keep
saying "Dad"
at the end of every sentence?

612
00:47:35,450 --> 00:47:38,080
I'm sorry. I didn't realize
I was doing it, Dad.

613
00:47:38,080 --> 00:47:39,520
Sorry, Dad.

614
00:47:42,560 --> 00:47:46,490
Do you want to know
why I keep saying "Dad?"
The truth?

615
00:47:46,490 --> 00:47:49,060
'Cause you missed
your old man so much, right?

616
00:47:49,060 --> 00:47:50,160
Exactly.

617
00:47:51,530 --> 00:47:53,600
It's because in my whole life

618
00:47:53,600 --> 00:47:57,070
I mean, you know,
for the past eight weeks -

619
00:47:57,070 --> 00:48:02,270
I was never able to say the
word "Dad."
Never. Not once.

620
00:48:02,270 --> 00:48:07,150
And if you ask me, a dad
is an irreplaceable person
in a girl's life.

621
00:48:07,150 --> 00:48:11,250
Think about it. There's a
whole day
devoted to celebrating fathers

622
00:48:11,250 --> 00:48:14,090
Just imagine someone's life
without a father.

623
00:48:14,090 --> 00:48:16,050
Never buying a Father's
Day card.

624
00:48:16,060 --> 00:48:18,220
Never sitting on their
father's lap.

625
00:48:18,220 --> 00:48:20,190
Never being able to say,
"Hi, Dad!"

626
00:48:20,190 --> 00:48:23,290
or, "What's up, Dad?"
or, "Catch you later, Dad."

627
00:48:23,300 --> 00:48:26,330
I mean, a baby's first words
are always "Dada,
" aren't they?

628
00:48:26,330 --> 00:48:30,570
Let me see if I get this.
You missed being able to
call me "Dad?"

629
00:48:30,570 --> 00:48:34,070
Yeah. I really have, Dad.

630
00:48:41,210 --> 00:48:43,680
Oh, my God. Oh, my God.

631
00:48:43,680 --> 00:48:46,520
Now you're starting
to sound like your old self.

632
00:49:04,640 --> 00:49:05,570
<i>(dog barks)</i>

633
00:49:07,340 --> 00:49:10,340
<i>(shrieks)</i> Hello, gorgeous!

634
00:49:13,250 --> 00:49:15,580
Oh, look at you!

635
00:49:15,580 --> 00:49:17,720
Oh, you grew.

636
00:49:17,720 --> 00:49:22,150
Oh, we missed you so much.

637
00:49:22,150 --> 00:49:23,490
Hey. Don't you dare
let your old man

638
00:49:23,490 --> 00:49:25,420
talk you out of going back to
camp, OK?

639
00:49:25,420 --> 00:49:27,230
You're a growing girl.
You need adventure.

640
00:49:27,230 --> 00:49:28,360
OK.

641
00:49:28,360 --> 00:49:32,430
